4 Section 3. Section 61-8-1002, MCA, is amended to read:
5 "61-8-1002. Driving under influence. (1) A person commits the offense of driving under the influence
6 if the person drives or is in actual physical control of:
7 (a) a vehicle or a commercial motor vehicle upon the ways of this state open to the public while
8 under the influence of alcohol, any drug, or a combination of alcohol and any drug;
9 (b) a noncommercial vehicle upon the ways of this state open to the public while the person's
10 alcohol concentration, as shown by analysis of the person's blood, breath, oral fluid, or other bodily substance,
11 is 0.08 or more;
12 (c) a commercial motor vehicle within this state while the person's alcohol concentration, as shown
13 by analysis of the person's blood, breath, oral fluid, or other bodily substance, is 0.04 or more;
14 (d) a noncommercial vehicle or commercial motor vehicle within this state while the person's
15 tetrahydrocannabinol level, excluding inactive metabolites, as shown by analysis of the person's blood or other
16 bodily substance, is 5 ng/ml or more; or
17 (e) a vehicle within this state when the person is under 21 years of age at the time of the offense
18 while the person's alcohol concentration, as shown by analysis of the person's blood, breath, oral fluid, or other
19 bodily substance, is 0.02 or more.
20 (2) Upon the trial of any civil or criminal action or proceeding arising out of acts alleged to have
21 been committed by any person driving or in actual physical control of a vehicle while under the influence of
22 alcohol, the concentration of alcohol in the person at the time of a test, as shown by analysis of a sample of the
23 person's blood, breath, oral fluid, or other bodily substance drawn or taken within a reasonable time after the
24 alleged act, gives rise to the following inferences:
25 (a) if there was at that time an alcohol concentration of 0.04 or less, it may be inferred that the
26 person was not under the influence of alcohol;
27 (b) if there was at that time an alcohol concentration in excess of 0.04 but less than 0.08, that fact
28 may not give rise to any inference that the person was or was not under the influence of alcohol, but the fact
